    {
      "id": "e34922f5_83f5fa96",
      "file_path": "controlloop/common/controller-tdjam/src/main/java/org/onap/policy/controlloop/tdjam/TdjamController.java",
      "patchset_number": 17,
      "line": 89,
      "message": "As far as I know from source code, 'VirtualControlLoopEvent' is inherited from ControlLoopEvent, and mainly using for ONSET in vCPE use case. I am not sure that a super type that could be referenced here would get any benefit for any other events. If you could explain more...",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 2477,
        "name": "Takamune Cho",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "takamune.cho@att.com",
        "username": "Takamune_Cho"
      },
      "updated": "2020-08-27 21:57:23.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "359542b7_5f753280",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "6b7616c8_4f3025d8",
      "file_path": "controlloop/common/controller-tdjam/src/main/java/org/onap/policy/controlloop/tdjam/TdjamController.java",
      "patchset_number": 17,
      "line": 89,
      "message": "In terms of event types, the standard 'VirtualControlLoopEvent' class used in the ONAP use cases may not be suitable for the onsets used inside of a particular company. There can be vastly different event types that don't match the 'VirtualControlLoopEvent' schema. This was one of the motivations behind the recent work Jim has been doing with the rules restructuring, to be able to support different event types with different event managers. So it would be nice if the TDJAM controller could work for other use cases that are not ONAP specific. At least for my use cases, this feature would not be usable and I would think that is the case for other companies with custom event types as well.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 1677,
        "name": "Daniel Cruz",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "dc443y@att.com",
        "username": "dc443y"
      },
      "updated": "2020-08-27 22:07:09.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "e34922f5_83f5fa96",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "f693fa31_ac1f063f",
      "file_path": "controlloop/common/controller-tdjam/src/main/java/org/onap/policy/extension/system/NonDroolsPolicyController.java",
      "patchset_number": 20,
      "line": 496,
      "message": "POLICY-2806 to track on this. I put it on H-Rel",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 2477,
        "name": "Takamune Cho",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "takamune.cho@att.com",
        "username": "Takamune_Cho"
      },
      "updated": "2020-08-27 22:38:06.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "b61371d0_45a305f6",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "603e8aa4_f77a0943",
      "file_path": "controlloop/common/controller-tdjam/src/main/java/org/onap/policy/controlloop/tdjam/SerialWorkQueue.java",
      "patchset_number": 20,
      "line": 74,
      "message": "I don't think so.\n\nscenario A) two threads invoke start(): only the first invokes processQueue(), because the second returns via line 68\n\nscenario B) one thread invokes start(), another invokes queueAndRun() after synchronized block begins: first thread gets null on line 72 and does not invoke processQueue().  Second thread does not hit line 92 thus invokes processQueue()\n\nscenario C) one thread invokes start(), another invokes queueAndRun() and enters synchronized block first: second thread returns on line 92 when it finds it isn't running.  First thread gets the item added by the second thread and executes it on line 76\n\nscenario D) after start() completes, two threads invoke queueAndRun(): the first thread to synchronize will add an item and then process it.  Second thread will add its item and return via line 92 when it finds that the queue contains more than one item",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 811,
        "name": "Jim Hahn",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "jrh3@att.com",
        "username": "jrh3"
      },
      "updated": "2020-08-27 22:39:05.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "b6c641e8_7de80b69",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "97bb9d94_b40df6df",
      "file_path": "controlloop/common/controller-tdjam/src/main/java/org/onap/policy/controlloop/tdjam/TdjamController.java",
      "patchset_number": 17,
      "line": 89,
      "message": "What it really boils down to is, we can make the actors event-agnostic, but not the rules/application.  That's true of the new rules, even though they use event-agnostic actors, and it's also true of the TDJAM controller.  The new rules DO separate a lot of the utility code (i.e., java code) from the control (i.e., rules), but both the rules and most of the utility code are still specific to the ONAP usecases - hence they're placed inside controller-usecases.\n\nEven at the simplest level, the rules can't be event-agnostic, because they have to extract the request ID and enrichment data from the event, something that may not even be appropriate for other event types.\n\nIn other words, TDJAM is an interesting POC, but may not see a lot of use outside of straight-forward TOSCAs using plain VirtualControlLoopEvent.  Perhaps it can evolve into a more generic tool, but that would take a great deal of thought (and probably a lot of meta-programming in the TOSCA).",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 811,
        "name": "Jim Hahn",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "jrh3@att.com",
        "username": "jrh3"
      },
      "updated": "2020-08-27 22:39:05.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "6b7616c8_4f3025d8",
      "unresolved": true
    },
